      <title>Caesar’s Time and Wonder A Conversation with Patti Smith by Antonio Spadaro Full...</title>
      <link>https://www.instagram.com/p/DWUieaBiCam/</link>
      <description><![CDATA[<p><img src="https://scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.82787-15/657327227_18564757669061249_8334379342112826472_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_e35_p1080x1080_sh2.08_tt6&amp;_nc_cat=1&amp;ig_cache_key=Mzg2MDg2MjQwMzY3MjAyNDc0Mg%3D%3D.3-ccb7-5&amp;ccb=7-5&amp;_nc_sid=58cdad&amp;efg=eyJ2ZW5jb2RlX3RhZyI6InhwaWRzLjE0NDB4MTkyMC5zZHIuQzMifQ%3D%3D&amp;_nc_ohc=r2oEJfKMjXkQ7kNvwHII2oG&amp;_nc_oc=Adrz-PrV0kyd2IXdVo5m2ENsPe9E9i0IgO-QVBknxy9XK-IVbDTSBNjMZVVj_QaUnzw&amp;_nc_ad=z-m&amp;_nc_cid=0&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com&amp;_nc_gid=c5IZp7Gu7a8-UcXgkpbUjg&amp;_nc_ss=7a338&amp;oh=00_Afw8VV4QpmehonKShyc4RLgN1KgK2ny3YGP7rPnUhzV5kw&amp;oe=69CA32F3" alt="Instagram billede fra @thisispattismith" /></p><p><strong>@thisispattismith</strong></p><p>Caesar’s Time and Wonder<br/>
A Conversation with Patti Smith<br/>
by Antonio Spadaro<br/>
Full version in Commonweal https://www.commonwealmagazine.org/smith-patti-interview-spadaro-wonder<br/>
<br/>
Patti Smith writes every morning from eight to ten, seated at the same café, at the same corner table—always the same one. When I arrive, she is bent over a notebook, her pen moving with a patient, concentrated rhythm. I hesitate to interrupt her; she is clearly absorbed. But I step inside anyway, because outside it is brutally cold. My iPhone reports a wind chill of twenty-six degrees below zero, and I feel my body shivering from the inside out. She notices my decisive entrance and pauses, looks up, smiles. Then she dips back into the notebook and says, “Two more words.” A moment later she looks straight at me. “You are my inspiration,” she says, with a touch of irony and tenderness. “An inspiring interruption.”<br/>
<br/>
Inside the café there is a soft, enveloping warmth—the smell of coffee and toasted bread—and a pale winter light filtering through large windows. Patti is wearing a dark jacket, nothing conspicuous. She is seventy-nine years old, yet her presence is that of someone who has decided, with almost monastic discipline, never to stop paying attention to the world.<br/>
<br/>
We first met in Amsterdam. Ours is a friendship that resists easy explanation…</p>]]></description>
